<MainLayout title="PSCAD and PSS®E: when each model matters | IKAI Insights" description="PSCAD and PSS®E: when each model matters">
  <section class="page-hero"><div class="container"><span class="eyebrow light">IKAI Insight</span><h1>PSCAD and PSS®E: when each model matters</h1><p class="lead">Practical perspectives from IKAI Energy Consulting.</p></div></section>
  <section class="section"><article class="container prose">
    <p>PSS®E and PSCAD are both important power system tools, but they answer different types of questions.</p><h2>PSS®E for broad system behaviour</h2><p>PSS®E is commonly used for load flow, fault level, dynamic stability and large-scale network assessment. RMS simulation is efficient for examining system behaviour over wider areas and longer timeframes.</p><h2>PSCAD for fast electromagnetic behaviour</h2><p>PSCAD represents electromagnetic transients in much greater detail. It is particularly valuable for inverter controls, weak-grid behaviour, fast interactions and detailed fault response.</p><h2>One does not replace the other</h2><p>A project may perform well in RMS studies while still showing issues in EMT simulation. Equally, detailed EMT analysis does not remove the need to understand wider system behaviour.</p><p>The right approach is to define the engineering question first, then select the model and study method that can answer it credibly.</p>
